{"id": "4758", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=4758", "title": "Mental Domination", "text": "Mental Domination is a 4th level &lt;a href=\"priest%20spell\"&gt;priest spell&lt;/a&gt; only usable by &lt;a href=\"cleric\"&gt;cleric&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"paladin\"&gt;paladin&lt;/a&gt; classes. \nIt is nearly identical to the 5th level &lt;a href=\"wizard%20spell\"&gt;wizard spell&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Domination\"&gt;Domination&lt;/a&gt;, except that it casts slightly faster and ignores the natural Elven resistance to charm effects.\nGameplay.\nThe caster directs this spell towards a single target creature in range.\nWhen the spell is finished a magical projectile flies to the target creature and exposes it to the &lt;a href=\"Charmed\"&gt;Charmed&lt;/a&gt; effect.\nThe target must make a &lt;a href=\"Saving%20throw\"&gt;Saving throw&lt;/a&gt; versus spells with a 2=point penalty or will be charmed for spell's duration.\nIf charmed, the creature's allegiance changes to an Ally - and are considered a \"party member\" in terms of being friendly to the party.\nThis spell applies Charm Type 1003 to the target - \"Dire charmed - No text (Target hostile after effect ends)\".\nIf a player character is affected by this spell, they'll display an icon (No. 43) titled \"Domination\", and when the spell expires a sound effect will audible.\nAttacking or damaging actions towards the charmed creature ends the charmed state.\nIf a neutral target succeeds in their saving throw, they will not become hostile.\nAt least in &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20II\"&gt;Baldur's Gate II&lt;/a&gt;, the &lt;a href=\"Nymph%20Cloak\"&gt;Nymph Cloak&lt;/a&gt; or the &lt;a href=\"Ring%20of%20Human%20Influence\"&gt;Ring of Human Influence&lt;/a&gt; can be used to charm a \"person\" instead of this spell to apply a Charm Type 0 - \"Charmed (Target neutral after effect ends)\". \nThis spell can be blocked by &lt;a href=\"Magic%20resistance\"&gt;Magic resistance&lt;/a&gt;, or any spell protection that can handle a &lt;a href=\"Power%20level\"&gt;Power level&lt;/a&gt; 4 spell, such as &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Deflection\"&gt;Spell Deflection&lt;/a&gt;.\nA &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Immunity\"&gt;Spell Immunity: Enchantment&lt;/a&gt; will nullify this spell.\nNote that &lt;a href=\"Elf\"&gt;Elf&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Half-elf\"&gt;Half-elf&lt;/a&gt; creatures are not provided any resistance to this particular charm spell (this is consistent with the Advanced D&amp;D 2nd Edition spell).\nThe spell can be removed with any &lt;a href=\"Dispel%20Magic\"&gt;Dispel Magic&lt;/a&gt; effect.\nIn the &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20%28game%29\"&gt;Original&lt;/a&gt; and editions of BG1 only, many commoners and enemies have &lt;a href=\"Charmed\"&gt;hidden dialogues&lt;/a&gt; spoken only under charm. You may manually initiate dialogue with them by using the codice_1 button. These hidden dialogues are usually but simple and amusing quotes, but sometimes they do reveal more substantial clues.\nMod content.\n&lt;a href=\"Spell%20Revisions\"&gt;Spell Revisions&lt;/a&gt; mod has changed this Divine spell, revising its duration, and description. See below:\nMental Domination\nLevel: 4\nSchool: Enchantment\nSphere: Thought\nRange: Long\nDuration: 1 turn\nCasting Time: 4\nArea of Effect: 1 creature\nSaving Throw: Spell negates\nWhen cast upon a subject, he must make a save vs. spell at -2 in order to avoid the priest entering his mind. The effects of this spell are similar to the 5th level wizard spell Domination, with a few minor differences. Most notably, this spell gives the priest no access to the subject\u2019s thoughts, memory, or sensory apparatus. The priest simply is able to command the subject to perform certain tasks or functions during the spell duration. To control the subject, the priest must be within range and must be able to see the subject. This control will last until dispelled or for the duration of the spell."}
{"id": "17059", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=17059", "title": "Mephit", "text": "Mephits are pesky, &lt;a href=\"Imp\"&gt;Imp-like&lt;/a&gt;, extra-planar creatures first encountered in the &lt;a href=\"Dwarves_of_Dumathoin%23Exploring_the_Repository_of_Undeath\"&gt;Repository of Undeath&lt;/a&gt; and again throughout &lt;a href=\"Irenicus%27s%20Dungeon\"&gt;Irenicus's Dungeon&lt;/a&gt;. There are many varieties of these magical elemental creatures, each corresponding to one of the Inner Planes.\nTypes of Mephits encountered during the \"&lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20II\"&gt;Baldur's Gate II&lt;/a&gt;\" games include the following:\nBoth Mist and Steam Mephits originate from the quasi-elemental plane of Steam. There are no Vacuum and Ash Mephits in the game."}
{"id": "25159", "revid": "47673695", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=25159", "title": "Mephit Portal", "text": "Mephit Portals are doors to the Elemental Planes that keep on summoning until destroyed. They lack any defenses and have only 27 &lt;a href=\"Hit%20Dice\"&gt;Hit Points&lt;/a&gt;, but are immune to magic.\nLocation.\nAll four Portals present in the game can be found in &lt;a href=\"Irenicus%27s%20Dungeon%202nd%20Floor\"&gt;Irenicus's Dungeon 2nd Floor&lt;/a&gt;. Each portal connects to a specific Elemental Plane and will summon a different subtype of mephit (&lt;a href=\"Smoke%20Mephit\"&gt;Smoke&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Ice%20Mephit\"&gt;Ice&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Magma%20Mephit\"&gt;Magma&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Radiant%20Mephit\"&gt;Radiant&lt;/a&gt;, in that order from nearest to furthest), though statistically, they are identical to one another."}
