{"id": "32678", "revid": "46775035", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=32678", "title": "Missile damage", "text": "Missile damage is one of the 10 main &lt;a href=\"Damage\"&gt;damage types&lt;/a&gt; of the game, typically inflicted by ranged &lt;a href=\"weapons\"&gt;weapons&lt;/a&gt;, including &lt;a href=\"Throwing%20weapons\"&gt;throwing variants&lt;/a&gt; of axes, &lt;a href=\"daggers\"&gt;daggers&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"hammers\"&gt;hammers&lt;/a&gt;. For &lt;a href=\"bows\"&gt;bows&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"crossbows\"&gt;crossbows&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"slings\"&gt;slings&lt;/a&gt;, it is actually their &lt;a href=\"ammunition\"&gt;ammunition&lt;/a&gt; that inflicts the damage.\nProtection from missile.\nDamage from missile can be avoided or mitigated. Avoidance is provided by armor or shields that are solid and hard enough so that a projectile cannot penetrate it and reach the body. This is scored in the creature's &lt;a href=\"Armor%20Class\"&gt;Armor Class&lt;/a&gt; and penalties or bonuses can be applied specifically for missiles. Magical forms include protective auras and deflecting surfaces.\nMitigation is provided by armor, natural resistance and protective spells. Once a projectile pierces the armor, it is slowed down before penetrating a creature's skin. Both the thickness and sturdiness of the armor and a creatures skin mitigate the amount of damage the missile can still do."}
{"id": "32538", "revid": "3234315", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=32538", "title": "Missile weapon", "text": ""}
{"id": "32537", "revid": "3234315", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=32537", "title": "Missile weapons", "text": ""}
{"id": "11070", "revid": "31124876", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=11070", "title": "Missing Citizens", "text": "Citizens have been disappearing in &lt;a href=\"east%20Baldur%27s%20Gate\"&gt;east Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href=\"Scar\"&gt;Scar&lt;/a&gt; of the &lt;a href=\"Flaming%20Fist\"&gt;Flaming Fist&lt;/a&gt; wants someone to look into it.\nThis quest is given by Scar at the Flaming Fist Headquarters in &lt;a href=\"southwest%20Baldur%27s%20Gate\"&gt;southwest Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt;. After completing the investigation of &lt;a href=\"the%20Seven%20Suns\"&gt;the Seven Suns&lt;/a&gt;, he asks if the &lt;a href=\"Gorion%27s%20Ward\"&gt;Gorion's Ward&lt;/a&gt; and their party are interested in more work.\u00a0 If they say \u201cyes,\u201d he informs them that citizens are going missing in east Baldur's Gate and that he wants them to patrol the area and go down into the &lt;a href=\"sewers\"&gt;sewers&lt;/a&gt; and see what they can find. He gives the player 300 &lt;a href=\"Gold%20Piece\"&gt;gp&lt;/a&gt; up front and promises 1000 more upon completion of the quest.\nDirections.\nTo reach &lt;a href=\"east%20Baldur%27s%20Gate\"&gt;east Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt; from the Flaming Fist HQ, head east through the &lt;a href=\"South%20Baldur%27s%20Gate\"&gt;docks&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"southeast%20Baldur%27s%20Gate\"&gt;southeast Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt;. East Baldur's Gate has many sewer entrances. There are three around &lt;a href=\"Sorcerous%20Sundries\"&gt;Sorcerous Sundries&lt;/a&gt; to the west and one to the northeast between &lt;a href=\"Lucky%20Aello%27s%20Discount%20Store\"&gt;Lucky Aello's&lt;/a&gt; and the abandoned house. No matter which entrance the player chooses, they will come out in same part of the sewer. The only difference is which side of the room the party ends up on, which may have some strategic application.\nSewers.\nOnce in the &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20Sewers%20East\"&gt;sewers&lt;/a&gt;, the party will be confronted by an &lt;a href=\"Ogre%20Mage\"&gt;Ogre Mage&lt;/a&gt; who claims responsibility for the missing people. He used his &lt;a href=\"Carrion%20Crawler\"&gt;Carrion Crawler&lt;/a&gt;s to kill them and bring them to the sewers, where he looted the bodies and then fed them to his pets. After explaining his \"fiendishly clever\" scheme he attacks the party. Once dead, the ogre mage drops and some &lt;a href=\"random%20treasure\"&gt;random treasure&lt;/a&gt;, a &lt;a href=\"Ruby%20Ring\"&gt;Ruby Ring&lt;/a&gt; and a &lt;a href=\"Bastard%20Sword%20%2B1\"&gt;Bastard Sword +1&lt;/a&gt; or a &lt;a href=\"Scimitar%20%2B1\"&gt;Scimitar +1&lt;/a&gt; .\nTo the west of the junction where the ogre mage was found, there are several silk sacks holding bodies. The first sack contains a &lt;a href=\"Male%20Body\"&gt;Male Body&lt;/a&gt;, a ruby ring, and 135 gp.\u00a0The second sack contains another male body, a &lt;a href=\"Potion%20of%20Magic%20Protection\"&gt;Potion of Magic Protection&lt;/a&gt; and 51 gp. The third sack holds another male body and only 28 gp , or additionally contains a &lt;a href=\"Ninjat%C5%8D%20%2B1\"&gt;Ninjat\u014d +1&lt;/a&gt; . The last sack contains two male bodies, some &lt;a href=\"Murky%20Oil%20of%20Speed\"&gt;Murky Oil of Speed&lt;/a&gt; and 85 gp.\nIn the classic version of the game it doesn't count which of these or perhaps even other ruby rings is brought back to Scar for an extra reward of 3000 gp. In the Enhanced Edition this was changed, however, and only &lt;a href=\"Sashenstar%27s%20Ruby%20Ring\"&gt;Sashenstar's Ruby Ring&lt;/a&gt; (item code codice_1), dropped by the ogre is accepted.\nCompletion and Outcomes.\nReturn to Scar at the Flaming Fist HQ to complete the quest and collect the reward. Selecting option two (which explains the ogre mage's motivation for the killings) yields the greatest reward, as it allows the player to return the noblewoman's ring to get an extra bonus. Option three leaves out the motive and is apparently less pleasing to Scar, but still yields the agreed-upon reward of 1000 gp and 1000 XP.\nIf the player speaks to Scar and does not have the ruby ring, they will not be able to return it or collect the bonus. \nStrategy.\nThe ogre mage is capable of casting &lt;a href=\"Confusion%20%28wizard%29\"&gt;Confusion&lt;/a&gt; and summoning spells. The best strategy is to stop him from casting anything at all by killing him as soon as possible. &lt;a href=\"Arrow%20of%20Slaying\"&gt;Arrows of Slaying&lt;/a&gt; are ideal if they are available. Alternatively, having a mage cast &lt;a href=\"Agannazar%27s%20Scorcher\"&gt;Agannazar's Scorcher&lt;/a&gt; on him will speed things along considerably. Though the carrion crawlers will likely paralyze some party members before the ogre mage is killed. It may be advisable to keep a healer in ranged combat so they can heal paralyzed party members if it becomes necessary.\nMod content.\nUnfinished Business mod.\nOne of the components of Unfinished Business adds additional text to this quest and requires that players retrieve the noble's body as well as her ring for a reward. If the player speaks to Scar with the signet ring but without the noble's body, Scar will ask them to return to the sewers and search for it, promising an extra bonus. If the player refuses to return for the body, Scar will express his displeasure but will give the player a 500 gp bonus and 3000 XP. When both the ring and the body are returned to Scar, he rewards the player with 4000 gp and 3000 XP."}
{"id": "29770", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=29770", "title": "Missy", "text": "Missy is a female &lt;a href=\"Shadow%20Thieves\"&gt;Shadow Thief&lt;/a&gt; who holds the distinct position of being &lt;a href=\"Aran%20Linvail\"&gt;Aran Linvail&lt;/a&gt;'s \"coat check girl\". She is found in the coat room of the secret &lt;a href=\"Aran%20Linvail%27s%20Hideout\"&gt;hideout&lt;/a&gt; just waiting with a wonderfully cheerful attitude to take your coat.\nDialogue.\n\"Hey! Hey, you! Give me your damn coat... NOW!\"\nTrivia.\n were a common phenomenon in night clubs of yore. They would store your outerwear in a secure location and give you a claim tag for when you left. Missy, however, may employ a more pickpocketing interpretation of the phrase."}
{"id": "29773", "revid": "31124876", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=29773", "title": "Missy (cat)", "text": "Missy the &lt;a href=\"Cats\"&gt;cat&lt;/a&gt; can be found hanging around the bow of the &lt;a href=\"Slaver%20Stockade\"&gt;Slaver Stockade&lt;/a&gt; in the &lt;a href=\"Athkatla%20Slums\"&gt;Athkatla Slums&lt;/a&gt; district, except for a couple hours around midnight. It is unknown, where she's staying and if she's somehow related to &lt;a href=\"Missy\"&gt;Missy&lt;/a&gt; the coat check girl."}
{"id": "28984", "revid": "3234315", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=28984", "title": "Mist", "text": ""}
{"id": "51298", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=51298", "title": "Mist Ball", "text": "Mist Ball is an innate ability effect available to most &lt;a href=\"Mist%20Mephit\"&gt;Mist Mephit&lt;/a&gt; creatures in the game saga. \nEffects.\nThe spell effect is uninterruptable and takes almost no time to deploy. A sparkling projectile is launched at a single target in range. It will strike the target and inflict a 10 second duration &lt;a href=\"Blindness\"&gt;Blindness&lt;/a&gt; status effect, along with a \"Blinded\" text message on the screen event display, and a blindness icon on the target's portrait. In addition to this, the target must attempt a &lt;a href=\"Saving%20throw\"&gt;Saving throw&lt;/a&gt; vs. Breath Attack to negate a energy damage wound.\nThe innate ability can be blocked by magic resistance and has level 2 spell power, and thus could be blocked by spell protections like &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Deflection\"&gt;Spell Deflection&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"Minor%20Globe%20of%20Invulnerability\"&gt;Minor Globe of Invulnerability&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "2086", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=2086", "title": "Mist Horror", "text": "Mist Horror is a monster that's usually found in the company of &lt;a href=\"Crimson%20Death\"&gt;Crimson Death&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Vampiric%20Mist\"&gt;Vampiric Mist&lt;/a&gt;, and other mist-type monsters. In areas where they are encountered, they usually only appear as a spawned creature, except for the &lt;a href=\"Forest%20of%20Tethir%20%28Shadows%20of%20Amn%29\"&gt;Forest of Tethir&lt;/a&gt; area and inside &lt;a href=\"Coran%27s%20Cabin\"&gt;Coran's Cabin&lt;/a&gt;.\nGameplay.\nThey are immune to weapons less than +2 enchantment. They have complete immunity to acid, cold (including magical cold) and poison damage, and 50% &lt;a href=\"Magic%20resistance\"&gt;Magic resistance&lt;/a&gt;.\nA Mist Horror's tendril-like melee attack weapon inflicts a 2d8 &lt;a href=\"Crushing%20damage\"&gt;Crushing&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"Slashing%20damage\"&gt;Slashing&lt;/a&gt; (selected by the AI regarding the most favorable THAC0 value on the target). Additionally, 1d8 &lt;a href=\"Cold%20damage\"&gt;Cold damage&lt;/a&gt; is applied. The cold damage is the elemental type and is unaffected by magic resistance or &lt;a href=\"Power%20level\"&gt;Power level&lt;/a&gt; spell protections.\nEach successful weapon strike on a target has a 30% probability to cause a &lt;a href=\"Panic\"&gt;Panic&lt;/a&gt; effect as well as a -10 &lt;a href=\"Morale\"&gt;Morale&lt;/a&gt; modifier reduction, with a duration of 5 rounds. A &lt;a href=\"Saving%20throw\"&gt;Saving throw&lt;/a&gt; vs. spell with a -2 penalty will negate these effects. Magic resistance can block these, but &lt;a href=\"Power%20level\"&gt;Power level&lt;/a&gt; spell protections will not.\nMod content.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; mod makes some revisions to this creature. A new AI attack script is assigned that allows the creature to innately cast a {SPIN674.spl) &lt;a href=\"Chaos\"&gt;Chaos&lt;/a&gt; effect in a radius around itself. This can be done initially when an enemy is detected on a timed basis afterwards (5 rounds). A saving throw is allowed."}
{"id": "48969", "revid": "773742", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=48969", "title": "Mist Mephit", "text": "A Mist Mephit is an extra-planar \"outsider\" (i.e., linked to various Elemental, Quasi-Elemental and Outer planes of existence). These creatures are similar to &lt;a href=\"Imp\"&gt;Imps&lt;/a&gt;, and are found in a number of areas during the &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20II\"&gt;\"Baldur's Gate II\"&lt;/a&gt; games.\nGameplay.\nA Mist Mephit can attack twice per round in melee for damage. It also has the innate &lt;a href=\"Mist%20Ball\"&gt;Mist Ball&lt;/a&gt; ability. \nThe mephit will initiate the \"Mist Ball\" attack, which launches a sparkling projectile at a target in range and it deals damage. In addition, the attack obscures the target's vision, and induces a &lt;a href=\"Blindness\"&gt;Blindness&lt;/a&gt; status effect lasting 10 seconds. A &lt;a href=\"Saving%20throw\"&gt;Saving throw&lt;/a&gt; vs. Breath Attack will negate the magical energy damage, but there is no save against the blindness effect. \nThe Mist Mephit can attempt this innate ability as soon as an enemy is detected and if within range. After the initial launch, at least two rounds may pass before attempting another one. After every 5 rounds after the initial launch, the creature reevaluates the available targets and starts the cycle over, although it is unlikely the fragile creature will survive that long, as the mephit is also scripted to engage in melee combat as well. \nThe Mist Mephit has no magic, physical damage or elemental resistance. The InfoBox summarizes their special abilities and immunities to certain status effects. The game has the creature with a memorized &lt;a href=\"Blur\"&gt;Blur&lt;/a&gt; spell but it isn't scripted to use it, so it is probably just a developer creature file copy-paste remnant.\nNotes.\nThe game files provide for a Mist Mephit &lt;a href=\"Find%20Familiar\"&gt;familiar&lt;/a&gt;, however this type is not implemented for use in an unmodified game."}
{"id": "45256", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=45256", "title": "Mistress Ada", "text": "Mistress Ada is the head priestess of &lt;a href=\"Talos\"&gt;Talos&lt;/a&gt; in the &lt;a href=\"Temple%20of%20Talos\"&gt;Temple of Talos&lt;/a&gt; located in &lt;a href=\"Athkatla\"&gt;Athkatla&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Temple%20District\"&gt;Temple District&lt;/a&gt; during the \"\" campaign.\nGameplay.\nDuring nighttime hours, Ada is sleeping in her chambers in the Temple. During the day she administers temple services and runs the store.\nShe also wears the &lt;a href=\"Necklace%20of%20Talos\"&gt;Necklace of Talos&lt;/a&gt;, but only in her daytime form. The sleeping form doesn't wear the necklace, and that item is within the chest in her quarters while she slumbers. This item may be required as ordered by &lt;a href=\"Mae%27Var\"&gt;Mae'Var&lt;/a&gt; as part of the &lt;a href=\"Find%20Proof%20of%20Mae%27Var%27s%20Treachery\"&gt;Find Proof of Mae'Var's Treachery&lt;/a&gt; questline.\nTemple services.\nAda takes donations and offers services.\nTemple of Talos store.\nMistress Ada can sell items and identify them, but does not buy from the party, nor can you steal from her.\nMod content.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Alternatives\"&gt;Alternatives&lt;/a&gt; mod presents a dialogue path that offers a different way to satisfy Mae Var's demand that the protagonist steal an artifact from this temple. The dialogue selection choices will automatically be presented as an optional path if the player wishes to pursue that action."}
