{"id": "38293", "revid": "46775035", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=38293", "title": "Monster Summoning", "text": "Monster Summoning is the name of an archetypal &lt;a href=\"Wizard\"&gt;Wizard&lt;/a&gt; conjuration spell that can, as its name suggests, be used to summon a variety of random &lt;a href=\"monster\"&gt;monster&lt;/a&gt;s. This spell is broken into multiple sub-spells, differentiated by numerical value; the higher the sub-spell's numerical value, the more powerful the creatures that it can summon.\nIn the tabletop game, Monster Summoning could reach as high as Monster Summoning VII (7); this is because &lt;a href=\"Monster%20Summoning%20I\"&gt;Monster Summoning I&lt;/a&gt; is a 3rd level spell, and there are only 9 levels of wizard spells. However, in the Baldur's Gate games, only the first three Monster Summoning sub-spells - &lt;a href=\"Monster%20Summoning%20I\"&gt;Monster Summoning I&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Monster%20Summoning%20II\"&gt;Monster Summoning II&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Monster%20Summoning%20III\"&gt;Monster Summoning III&lt;/a&gt; - can be learned.\nIn 3rd edition, the spell family was renamed \"Summon Monster\" and was altered into a set of nine spells, one for each spell level from 1st to 9th."}
