{"id": "4109", "revid": "46775035", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=4109", "title": "Potions", "text": "This article contains a complete list of all potions that appeared in Baldur's Gate and its enhanced edition, as well as Baldur's Gate II. It is used to quickly view information. Specific information can be found at the page of the potion self and should not be added here.\nList of potions.\nThis is an alphabetical list of normal potions. For a list of murky potions click &lt;a href=\"Murky%20potions\"&gt;here&lt;/a&gt;. On this list the type of potion is listed first and then other identifying information is listed. For example Marek's Potion of Antidote is listed as Antidote, Marek's Potion of.\nPotions with potentially unlimited availability in BG2(EE).\nThis is an alphabetical list of potions to which the player can acquire unlimited access via &lt;a href=\"Alchemy\"&gt;Alchemy&lt;/a&gt; (available at high-levels for both &lt;a href=\"Thief\"&gt;Thieves&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Bard\"&gt;Bards&lt;/a&gt;), the &lt;a href=\"Mage%20Stronghold\"&gt;Mage Stronghold&lt;/a&gt; apprentice &lt;a href=\"Morul\"&gt;Morul&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"Wish\"&gt;Wish&lt;/a&gt; (available to anyone capable of using arcane scrolls and unlimitedly so via learning the spell or using the scroll with a clone).\nUnlike the other two methods, Morul becomes unavailable once the player transitions out of Shadows of Amn and into Throne of Bhaal. So if the player is fond of potions like Potions of Fire Breath (that are only available unlimitedly from Morul), they might want to stock up on said potions before leaving that portion of the game.\nFinally, the \"x\"s on the table denote which sources offer which potions (eg Oils of Speed are available unlimitedly from all three sources)."}
