{"id": "51832", "revid": "53032777", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=51832", "title": "Prin", "text": "Prin is a &lt;a href=\"Alignment\"&gt;Neutral Good&lt;/a&gt; female &lt;a href=\"Elf\"&gt;Elf&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Bard\"&gt;Bard&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;a href=\"Gorion%27s%20Ward\"&gt;Gorion's Ward&lt;/a&gt; can meet her during &lt;a href=\"Chapter%20Eight%20%E2%80%93%20Coast%20Way%20Crossing\"&gt;chapter eight&lt;/a&gt; of \"\", in &lt;a href=\"Coast%20Way%20Crossing\"&gt;Coast Way Crossing&lt;/a&gt;.\nLocation.\nThis joyful Bard is probably the first person Gorion's Ward will meet upon starting to explore the map outside the &lt;a href=\"Flaming%20Fist\"&gt;Flaming Fist&lt;/a&gt; camp. She can be found singing next to an ancient menhir with strange glowing runes, a little further up the road northeast of the camp, south of the burned inn.\nQuests.\nWhen the &lt;a href=\"party\"&gt;party&lt;/a&gt; talks to her, and follows the right dialogue choices, Prin gives them the &lt;a href=\"Ancient%20Menhirs\"&gt;Ancient Menhirs&lt;/a&gt; quest. She explains that she was singing while walking, and she heard a menhir humming back to her. Then she found out that there are more like this around the area, and they all behave the same. When she sang to more than one, their tones lasted longer, but all eventually stopped. She has no objection at all if the party tells her that they want to sing to the menhirs. She might actually mark their location on the map, if they ask where she found them. And in the end, Prin will ask the party to come back and let her know if hey find all the ancient menhirs and learn why they're singing. If they completed the quest correctly, upon returning she will reward them with the &lt;a href=\"Reed%20of%20Echoes\"&gt;Reed of Echoes&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "18130", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=18130", "title": "Prince Villynaty", "text": "Prince Villynaty is a &lt;a href=\"sahuagin\"&gt;sahuagin&lt;/a&gt; located in the &lt;a href=\"City%20of%20Caverns\"&gt;City of Caverns&lt;/a&gt; in \"Shadows of Amn \"campaign.\nGameplay.\nThis noble is the leader of the Rebel Faction in the &lt;a href=\"Underwater%20City\"&gt;City of Caverns&lt;/a&gt; and opposed to &lt;a href=\"King%20Ixilthetocal\"&gt;King Ixilthetocal&lt;/a&gt;. \nIf for any reason that the party is in combat with the Prince, the creature will behave as a spear wielding melee fighting opponent. If this occurs, all rebel faction creatures will also be hostile against the party as well.\nAttention directed to the special items the prince has upon its person and the unique weapon it wields, this applies to the creature displayed in the InfoBox. Pickpocketing rules apply to these items. \nNote.\nThere is a second Prince Villynaty creature file (SAHPRE2) used in the game - That version is equipped with the &lt;a href=\"MINHP1.ITM\"&gt;MINHP1.ITM&lt;/a&gt; to make it immune to death or destruction. This version is substituted during certain scenes and portions of the questline in order to preserve the game being able to execute essential scripts without causing plot glitches or game failure if the creature were to be destroyed.\nMod content.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; mod makes some changes. It provides a tactical AI script for smarter combat behavior. The Prince is assigned a Fighter class. Spear weapon grand mastery proficiency is also assigned, to correct the unmodified creature coding, and 2 pips in two-handed fighting style. Strength, HP and APR are raised a little. A use of &lt;a href=\"Power%20Attack\"&gt;Power Attack&lt;/a&gt; is provided. A &lt;a href=\"Potion%20of%20Magic%20Shielding\"&gt;Potion of Magic Shielding&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Potion%20of%20Extra%20Healing\"&gt;Potion of Extra Healing&lt;/a&gt; are scripted for quaffing."}
{"id": "5403", "revid": "31124876", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=5403", "title": "Prism", "text": "Prism is an artist from &lt;a href=\"Nashkel\"&gt;Nashkel&lt;/a&gt; who is encountered in the &lt;a href=\"Nashkel%20Mines\"&gt;Nashkel Mines&lt;/a&gt; area.\nAfter having stolen some &lt;a href=\"emerald\"&gt;emerald&lt;/a&gt;s, he moved to the Nashkel Mines, where he has been working for days without sleep on a sculpture of &lt;a href=\"Ellesime\"&gt;Ellesime&lt;/a&gt;, a queen of the &lt;a href=\"Elf\"&gt;elves&lt;/a&gt; he once saw on a trip to &lt;a href=\"Evereska\"&gt;Evereska&lt;/a&gt;. The emeralds shall become the sparkling eyes of his work which he is carving out of a rock.\n&lt;br&gt;\nLike &lt;a href=\"Oublek\"&gt;Oublek&lt;/a&gt;, he first takes &lt;a href=\"Gorion%27s%20Ward\"&gt;Gorion's Ward&lt;/a&gt; for &lt;a href=\"Greywolf\"&gt;Greywolf&lt;/a&gt; or his henchmen, who he assumes will be after him for the theft. The party then can decide how to progress with the &lt;a href=\"Quests\"&gt;quest&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Prism%20the%20Sculptor\"&gt;Prism the Sculptor&lt;/a&gt;.\nTrivia.\nPrism is mention by four different characters in the and once during the :\n&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;\n&lt;a href=\"Dawnbringer%20Sain\"&gt;Dawnbringer Sain&lt;/a&gt; in the &lt;a href=\"Temple%20of%20Lathander%20%28Temple%20District%29\"&gt;Temple of Lathander&lt;/a&gt; \u2014\n&lt;br&gt;\n&lt;a href=\"Guardian%20Telwyn\"&gt;Guardian Telwyn&lt;/a&gt; in the &lt;a href=\"Temple%20of%20Helm%20%28Temple%20District%29\"&gt;Temple of Helm&lt;/a&gt; \u2014\n&lt;br&gt;\n&lt;a href=\"High%20Watcher%20Oisig\"&gt;High Watcher Oisig&lt;/a&gt; in the Temple of Helm \u2014\n&lt;br&gt;\n&lt;a href=\"Talon%20Yarryl\"&gt;Talon Yarryl&lt;/a&gt; in the &lt;a href=\"Temple%20of%20Talos%20%28Temple%20District%29\"&gt;Temple of Talos&lt;/a&gt; \u2014\n&lt;br&gt;\n&lt;a href=\"Dennation\"&gt;Dennation&lt;/a&gt; before Tier 1 - Battle 5 \u2014 "}
{"id": "8435", "revid": "1476364", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=8435", "title": "Prism's Emeralds", "text": ""}
{"id": "7072", "revid": "39868911", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=7072", "title": "Prism the Sculptor", "text": "Prism the Sculptor, also known as\u00a0Prism's Emeralds, is a side-quest in &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20%28game%29\"&gt;Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt; and the .\nAcquisition.\nThe quest is given by &lt;a href=\"Oublek\"&gt;Oublek&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0in\u00a0&lt;a href=\"Nashkel\"&gt;Nashkel&lt;/a&gt;.\nWalkthrough.\nThe bounty is to return two &lt;a href=\"emerald\"&gt;emerald&lt;/a&gt;s which were stolen by &lt;a href=\"Prism\"&gt;Prism&lt;/a&gt;, who disappeared after the theft and Oublek doesn't care what approach is taken.\nPrism can be found in the area of &lt;a href=\"Nashkel%20Mines\"&gt;Nashkel Mines&lt;/a&gt;, where he is carving a face in a rock wall, in the southwest corner of the map. There are several ways to approach the quest.\nKill Prism.\nPrism dies and the emeralds can be taken.\nLetting Prism finish his work.\nIf he is allowed to finish his work, the bounty hunter &lt;a href=\"Greywolf\"&gt;Greywolf&lt;/a&gt; will appear and begin a conversation, presenting another two options:\nIf Prism is not defended, Greywolf kills Prism and takes the emeralds then disappears and the quest can't be completed.\nIf prevented from killing Prism, Greywolf will attack the party and his death will net , 102 &lt;a href=\"Gold%20Piece\"&gt;gold pieces&lt;/a&gt;, and the weapon &lt;a href=\"Varscona\"&gt;Varscona&lt;/a&gt; as loot from his corpse. Shortly after the fight, Prism manages to complete his work and then dies from exhaustion while the party is rewarded 1000 XP and +1 &lt;a href=\"Reputation\"&gt;Reputation&lt;/a&gt;. Before his death, he reveals that the subject of his work is &lt;a href=\"Ellesime\"&gt;Ellesime&lt;/a&gt;.\nIf you pickpocket the two emeralds, Prism will walk away when you speak to him, yielding no further rewards for the party.\nTurning in the gems.\nAfter Prism's fate is decided, the emeralds can be taken either from his corpse or pried from the sculpture. Unfortunately, the reward received for returning to Oublek with the gems is only 300 gold pieces, which is 1,200 gold lower than if they are sold to a merchant.\nEven if sold, the quest can still be completed later, if another two emeralds are gained. However, if at least two emeralds are in the group's inventory, the &lt;a href=\"The%20Tale%20of%20Captain%20Brage\"&gt;bounty for Captain Brage&lt;/a&gt; cannot be turned into Oublek without also triggering returning the gems.\nIn your Journal.\nYou will likely have rumor-based entries for Prism the Sculptor in your\u00a0&lt;a href=\"Journal\"&gt;Journal&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0before you actually receive the quest from Oublek. When you ask him about available bounties, the following entries will be added to your Journal:\nUpon completion:\nAchievements.\nIn \"\", there are two &lt;a href=\"achievements\"&gt;achievements&lt;/a&gt; that can be earned from this quest:\nMod content.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Unfinished%20Business%20for%20BG1\"&gt;Unfinished Business for BG1&lt;/a&gt; mod revises some aspects of this encounter with prism, to include restoring a story element, dialogue and some other minor results of certain player actions."}
{"id": "5833", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=5833", "title": "Prismatic Spray", "text": "Prismatic Spray not only blinds a creature, but there are also seven other additional random effects possible.\nGameplay.\nThe caster directs this spell in a spray \"fan\" area of effect that widens laterally as the multi-colored rays spread out, and travel up to 15 feet distance from the caster - select the direction of the fan area using the targeting cursor.\nUpon completion of the spell, a multicolored spray will fan out from the caster (and the caster's sprite will automatically face in the direction of the spray).\nDespite the spell's description that \"any creature\" in the spell's spray can potentially be affected, this particular spell won't affect anything except enemy creatures.\nAny enemy creature in the spray will be exposed to an individual random probability of a &lt;a href=\"Blindness\"&gt;Blindness&lt;/a&gt; status effect, and 1 or 2 other effects.\nThis spell (like any other probabilistic spell in the game) rolls a number between 0 and 99 to determine which effects take place on a failed save (with some overlap allowing for 2 effects to occur at once, as the description states):\n0-14 = 20 magic damage, save vs spells for half\n12-29 = 40 magic damage, save vs spells for half\n27-44 = 80 magic damage, save vs spells for half\n42-59 = 100% of a target's HP in poison damage, save vs poison to only take 20 damage\n57-73 = petrification, save vs polymorph/petrification to avoid\n71-87 = feeblemindedness, save vs wand to avoid\n85-99 = disintegration, save vs spell to avoid\nThis means that there's an 18% chance for targets to roll two saves, a 58% chance for them to roll against an instant death effect (feeblemind is essentially death for the protagonist, as the target is left completely helpless) and a 9% chance for them to roll against two instant death effects.\nMoreover, the fact that the poison damage does 100% of a target's HP in damage means it can theoretically kill an enemy that might be immune to every other instant death effect, but vulnerable to poison.\nThis spell can be blocked by &lt;a href=\"Magic%20resistance\"&gt;Magic resistance&lt;/a&gt; or negated by &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Immunity\"&gt;Spell Immunity: Conjuration&lt;/a&gt;.\nAll the spell's lingering effects can be removed with a &lt;a href=\"Dispel%20Magic\"&gt;Dispel Magic&lt;/a&gt; effect, except for the &lt;a href=\"Petrified\"&gt;Petrified&lt;/a&gt; effect.\nNotes.\nThe projectile for this spell, is possibly miscoded and is excluding party members from being affected. All creatures in the AoE should be exposed to the spell.\nTrivia.\nThis spell first appeared as \"The Excellent Prismatic Spray\" in the book &lt;a href=\"https%3A//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Dying_Earth\"&gt;The Dying Earth&lt;/a&gt; (aka \"Mazirian the Magician\", collection of linked stories) by &lt;a href=\"https%3A//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jack_Vance\"&gt;Jack Vance&lt;/a&gt;.\nThe Advanced Dungeons and Dragons 2nd Edition Wizard spell \"Prismatic Spray\" has some differences than the BG game's version. Instead of being feebleminded, it can cause insanity, and rather than disintegration, a victim is sent to another plane. The Pen and Paper spell has 70x15 feet spray effect. But the largest difference is that anyone in the spray can be affected, there is no immunity for the caster and allies.\nMod content.\n&lt;a href=\"Spell%20Revisions\"&gt;Spell Revisions&lt;/a&gt; mod has changed this arcane spell, revising its Spell School, casting time, saving throw, effects, and description. See below:\nPrismatic Spray\nLevel: 7\nSchool: Alteration\nRange: Special\nDuration: Special\nCasting Time: 1\nArea of Effect: Cone\nSaving Throw: Special\nWhen this spell is cast, the wizard causes seven shimmering, multicolored rays of light to flash from his hand. These include all colors of the visible spectrum; each ray has a different power and purpose. Any creature with fewer than 8 Hit Dice struck by a ray is blinded for 5 rounds, regardless of any other effect. Any creature that is caught within the area of effect will be touched by one or more rays. The effects of the rays are listed below, and all saves are made at a -4 penalty.\nRed - 10d6 points of fire damage (save vs. breath half)\nOrange - 10d6 points of acid damage (save vs. breath half)\nYellow - 10d6 points of electrical damage (save vs. breath half)\nGreen - Death (save vs. poison reduces to 20 poison damage)\nBlue - Permanently stunned (save vs. polymorph neg.)\nIndigo - Feeblemind (save vs. wands neg.)\nViolet - Maze (save vs. spell neg.)"}
{"id": "49393", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=49393", "title": "Prison Captain (Cleric)", "text": "This Prison Captain &lt;a href=\"Cleric\"&gt;Cleric&lt;/a&gt; is part of a group of enemies that ambush anyone falling into her \"fleshy trap\" inside the &lt;a href=\"Planar%20Prison\"&gt;Planar Prison&lt;/a&gt;. She can be found nowhere else in the game. Some memorized spells won't be used as they are not scripted for selection.\nGameplay.\nThe priest will attempt to cast spells, but all of them can be interrupted by damage and the usual methods to disrupt. First it will try &lt;a href=\"Death%20Ward\"&gt;Death Ward&lt;/a&gt;, then &lt;a href=\"Blade%20Barrier\"&gt;Blade Barrier&lt;/a&gt;. If unmolested and able it may try to cast &lt;a href=\"Miscast%20Magic\"&gt;Miscast Magic&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Slay%20Living\"&gt;Slay Living&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Cause%20Serious%20Wounds\"&gt;Cause Serious Wounds&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Cause%20Critical%20Wounds\"&gt;Cause Critical Wounds&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Silence%2C%2015%27%20Radius\"&gt;Silence, 15' Radius&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href=\"Mental%20Domination\"&gt;Mental Domination&lt;/a&gt;. If the cleric is wounded to 50% of hit points, it will attempt to self-heal with &lt;a href=\"Cure%20Medium%20Wounds\"&gt;Cure Medium Wounds&lt;/a&gt;. \nOtherwise, the cleric will engage in close quarters combat with mace and shield. \nMod content.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; mod revises this cleric, especially with the \"Smarter Priest\" component. The creature will open hostilities with a series of uninterruptible self-buffs including &lt;a href=\"Armor%20of%20Faith\"&gt;Armor of Faith&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Spiritual%20Hammer\"&gt;Spiritual Hammer&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Draw%20Upon%20Holy%20Might%20%28spell%29\"&gt;Draw Upon Holy Might (spell)&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Free%20Action%20%28spell%29\"&gt;Free Action (spell)&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Chaotic%20Commands\"&gt;Chaotic Commands&lt;/a&gt;. \nIt will then attempt to summon a &lt;a href=\"Aerial%20Servant\"&gt;Aerial Servant&lt;/a&gt;, and then a &lt;a href=\"Skeleton%20Warrior\"&gt;Skeleton Warrior&lt;/a&gt;. The priest will engage in combat with the spiritual hammer anytime engaged in close quarters. There are other spells in this creature's arsenal, but it is unlikely to get a chance to use any of them past the first few rounds, due to its modest melee capability, and zero spell protections."}
{"id": "49395", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=49395", "title": "Prison Captain (Fighter)", "text": "This Prison Captain &lt;a href=\"Fighter\"&gt;Fighter&lt;/a&gt; is part of a group of enemies that ambush anyone falling into his \"fleshy trap\" inside the &lt;a href=\"Planar%20Prison\"&gt;Planar Prison&lt;/a&gt;. He can be found nowhere else in the game.\nGameplay.\nThis warrior is unlikely to try its crossbow and will switch to long sword and fight in melee with it.\nMod content.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; mod revises this warrior with a default SCS fighter AI script for smarter tactical behavior. 5 pips in crossbow and 3 pips in long sword weapon proficiency are added. The script is flipped from the unmodded creature, and the fighter attempts to fire &lt;a href=\"Bolt%20of%20Lightning\"&gt;Bolt of Lightning&lt;/a&gt; ammo, of which it now has 20 bolts. So as not to be put at disadvantage by melee combat, the warrior fights with the sword when forced to do so. "}
{"id": "49396", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=49396", "title": "Prison Captain (Fighter Mage)", "text": "These two &lt;a href=\"Elf\"&gt;Elven&lt;/a&gt; Prison Captain &lt;a href=\"Fighter%20/%20Mage\"&gt;Fighter/Mages&lt;/a&gt; are part of a group of enemies that ambush anyone falling into their \"fleshy traps\" inside the &lt;a href=\"Planar%20Prison\"&gt;Planar Prison&lt;/a&gt;. They can be found nowhere else in the game.\nGameplay.\nBoth F/M creatures use the same script for their actions. All of the spells in the Infobox are scripted for use, and no others. The creatures do not have any contingency force spell casts, and all attempted casts can be disrupted. It will open up with a &lt;a href=\"Protection%20From%20Magical%20Weapons\"&gt;Protection From Magical Weapons&lt;/a&gt; with short casting time of 1. It will them move through its list of spells\nin sequential order. For example, next would be &lt;a href=\"Mirror%20Image\"&gt;Mirror Image&lt;/a&gt;, then &lt;a href=\"Haste\"&gt;Haste&lt;/a&gt; and so forth. \nMod content.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; mod revises both creatures, and each one has a different default SCS \"Smarter Fighter Mage\" script, which results in slightly different spell casting. Here is a summary:"}
{"id": "49394", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=49394", "title": "Prison Captain (Mage)", "text": "This Prison Captain &lt;a href=\"Mage\"&gt;Mage&lt;/a&gt; is part of a group of enemies that ambush anyone falling into his \"fleshy trap\" inside the &lt;a href=\"Planar%20Prison\"&gt;Planar Prison&lt;/a&gt;. He can be found nowhere else in the game.\nGameplay.\nAt the opening of hostilities the mage will fire off a self-buff contingency containing &lt;a href=\"Stoneskin\"&gt;Stoneskin&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Protection%20From%20Normal%20Weapons\"&gt;Protection From Normal Weapons&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Protection%20From%20Electricity%20%28spell%29\"&gt;Protection From Electricity (spell)&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Minor%20Spell%20Deflection\"&gt;Minor Spell Deflection&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href=\"Shadow%20Door\"&gt;Shadow Door&lt;/a&gt;. After that will attempt a &lt;a href=\"Chain%20Lightning\"&gt;Chain Lightning&lt;/a&gt; cast at nearest enemy. \nIf there is a Mage or Cleric in the party will then attempt a &lt;a href=\"Power%20Word%2C%20Silence\"&gt;Power Word, Silence&lt;/a&gt;. \nFrom then on various attack spells will be tried and limited to the following: &lt;a href=\"Lightning%20Bolt\"&gt;Lightning Bolt&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Chaos\"&gt;Chaos&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Cone%20of%20Cold\"&gt;Cone of Cold&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Monster%20Summoning%20III\"&gt;Monster Summoning III&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Agannazar%27s%20Scorcher\"&gt;Agannazar's Scorcher&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Magic%20Missile\"&gt;Magic Missile&lt;/a&gt;. \nMod content.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; mod revises this mage and is now a specialist mage with Invoker kit. At the outset of the hostilities a contingency containing &lt;a href=\"Mirror%20Image\"&gt;Mirror Image&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Shadow%20Door\"&gt;Shadow Door&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Minor%20Globe%20of%20Invulnerability\"&gt;Minor Globe of Invulnerability&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Minor%20Spell%20Deflection\"&gt;Minor Spell Deflection&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Immunity\"&gt;Spell Immunity: Divination&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Shield%20%28spell%29\"&gt;Shield (spell)&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Protection%20From%20Normal%20Missiles\"&gt;Protection From Normal Missiles&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Stoneskin\"&gt;Stoneskin&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Non-Detection\"&gt;Non-Detection&lt;/a&gt; are launched.\nThe mage has other contingency spells ready when certain protections are removed, such as stoneskin, minor globe and protection from magic weapons.\nWhen the mage attempts offensive spell casts, those are determined by the SCS Smarter Mage AI based on available targets and their vulnerabilities. A number of damage dealing spells are in the mage's library such as Lightning Bolt, Ice Storm, and Disintegrate and disabling spells such as Teleport Field. Spell protection removal options are also in the repertoire like Breach, Remove Magic and Spell Thrust. The mage has a prepared &lt;a href=\"Minor%20Sequencer\"&gt;Minor Sequencer&lt;/a&gt; loaded with a double &lt;a href=\"Color%20Spray\"&gt;Color Spray&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "49080", "revid": "47673695", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=49080", "title": "Prison Guard", "text": "A Prison Guard is in charge of the prisoners in &lt;a href=\"The%20Prison\"&gt;The Prison&lt;/a&gt; in &lt;a href=\"Athkatla\"&gt;Athkatla's&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Athkatla%20Government\"&gt;Government District&lt;/a&gt; during the \"\" campaign.\nTwo of these guards serve under the &lt;a href=\"Prison%20Keeper\"&gt;Prison Keeper&lt;/a&gt;, and are currently in charge of two Prisoners, and possibly also &lt;a href=\"Jan%20Jansen\"&gt;Jan Jansen&lt;/a&gt;, if he was incarcerated by &lt;a href=\"Trax\"&gt;Trax&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "49078", "revid": "49426621", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=49078", "title": "Prison Keeper", "text": "The Prison Keeper is the man in charge of the guards and prisoners within &lt;a href=\"The%20Prison\"&gt;The Prison&lt;/a&gt;, located in &lt;a href=\"Athkatla\"&gt;Athkatla's&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Athkatla%20Government\"&gt;Government District&lt;/a&gt; during the \"\" campaign.\nRelated Quests.\nWith the right dialog choices during the sub-quest to Free Jan Jansen from prison, the Prison Keeper will offer to loan the party to take the gnome off his hands, as he is none-to-happy with the difficulty in containing the lil' rambunctious rebel.\"That gnome is the worst prisoner I ever had!\u00a0 He keeps picking the lock, complains about the food... even my hygiene!\u00a0 Just pay the 800gp and take him!\"\"Am I to be cursed with this gnome forever? You're driving me to drink! You and my mother, both. Take pity on a simple man... come back and pay the fine.\"\"... I guess I'll just cling to the hope that someone will bail him out... or buy me enough liquor to drink myself senseless.\"If the party takes the loan and pays him back after Jan's release, they earn a bit of experience. \"Excellent! He is free so, please, take him and go.\"\nFor more detail, see \"Recruitment\" on the page for &lt;a href=\"Jan%20Jansen\"&gt;Jan Jansen&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "38910", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=38910", "title": "Prison Warden", "text": "The Warden of the &lt;a href=\"Planar%20Prison\"&gt;Planar Prison&lt;/a&gt; is a demonic &lt;a href=\"Fighter\"&gt;Fighter&lt;/a&gt;/&lt;a href=\"Specialist%20Mage\"&gt;Conjurer&lt;/a&gt; whose presence stabilizes the pocket prison plane. The Warden must be defeated in order to weaken the bonds enough to escape back to the prime material plane and &lt;a href=\"Athkatla\"&gt;Athkatla&lt;/a&gt;.\nGameplay.\nThe demonic F/M with a Death Knight appearance will be located near its sadistic throne, along with any thralls and level dependent spawned creatures. The Warden does not venture away from this area unless it senses a party member in its detection range. Beware that it sees invisible and hidden creatures. \nThis demonic being only has moderate combat ability, with no proficiency with its wielded long sword &lt;a href=\"Adjatha%20the%20Drinker\"&gt;Adjatha the Drinker&lt;/a&gt;. This means it is really not a threat in melee combat. The developers may have made an error in its design, but regardless, it has certain mage like abilities, that cannot be disrupted and are mostly \"force-cast\". Some of the spells may get depleted through usage, and others have no limit. The creature also has no demonic immunities or protections, so any sort of weapon or elemental attack could work against it. It also has no inherent Magic resistance, which is unusual for a demonic creature. \nThe listing of memorized spells in the InfoBox is mostly accurate and reflects its capabilities. The scripted spells and spell attacks by the creature in the Classic and BG2EE version are nearly identical.\nExpect the creature to initially try and slay any freed thralls close by its throne area. The party may not be able to observe this, and it is likely the thralls will not last very long. Once the demon senses a party member, it will likely protect itself with a contingency of several self-buffs. \nThe creature will also attempt to dispel party members under certain status effects like Haste, Bless, Blur Improved Invisibility etc. Various damage dealing and disabling spells may be launched as well, and some will be bundled in sequencers. Instant death effects are possible from &lt;a href=\"Power%20Word%2C%20Kill\"&gt;Power Word, Kill&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Finger%20of%20Death%20%28wizard%29\"&gt;Finger of Death (wizard)&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"Disintegrate\"&gt;Disintegrate&lt;/a&gt; options, so be careful when approaching the fell entity.\nHaving the thralls freed will help in defeating it. The Warden will blast any liberated thralls with a Sunfire as soon as they are no longer under the Thrall Collar power. A well timed &lt;a href=\"Breach\"&gt;Breach&lt;/a&gt; and a &lt;a href=\"Haste\"&gt;Hasted&lt;/a&gt; fighter could make quick work of its rather mediocre 70 hit points. Due to his fantastic saving throw versus spells (1), you cannot count on the beast missing a save vs. spell.\nNote.\nThe Warden has no classification of gender in though it is male in the classic game .\nMod content.\nInstallation of the &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; Modification revises the Warden substantially. The creature is a level 18/18 Fighter/Conjurer. Statistics are changed including 18/76 STR, 16 DEX, 17 CON and 97 HP. It now has an adjusted Armor class of 0, and THAC0 of -2 with \"Adjatha the Drinker\". 2 pips in Long Sword weapon proficiency and 2 pips in single weapon fighting style are assigned. It now will strike 2.5 times per round with the sword. 50% Fire, Cold and 100% Electricity damage resistance is provided. \nThe Warden is also granted a base movement rate of 11 (2 faster than a regular humanoid), immunity to poison and poison damage, immunity to most Lightning based spells, and retains the ability to see the invisible.\nA new default AI script is implemented for the F/M class creature to improve tactical awareness, threat assessment and targeting behavior. New spell choices are also available. Expect the Warden to launch a series of uninterruptible self-protective buffs at the outset of hostilities to include &lt;a href=\"Mirror%20Image\"&gt;Mirror Image&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Improved%20Haste\"&gt;Improved Haste&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Minor%20Globe%20of%20Invulnerability\"&gt;Minor Globe of Invulnerability&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Turning\"&gt;Spell Turning&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Immunity\"&gt;Spell Immunity Divination&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Shield%20%28spell%29\"&gt;Shield (spell)&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Stoneskin\"&gt;Stoneskin&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href=\"Non-Detection\"&gt;Non-Detection&lt;/a&gt;. If the Warden suffers any damage then there is contingency that will launch a &lt;a href=\"Protection%20From%20Magical%20Weapons\"&gt;Protection From Magical Weapons&lt;/a&gt;, and this can occur up to two times during the battle.\nThe Warden will select offensive spells based on the AI's vulnerability assessments. Several Power word spells can be initiated with a casting time of 1, such as &lt;a href=\"Power%20Word%2C%20Blind\"&gt;Power Word, Blind&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Power%20Word%2C%20Stun\"&gt;Power Word, Stun&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Power%20Word%2C%20Kill\"&gt;Power Word, Kill&lt;/a&gt;. If the party is defended by spell protections or certain combat protections, then &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Thrust\"&gt;Spell Thrust&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Breach\"&gt;Breach&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href=\"Ruby%20Ray%20of%20Reversal\"&gt;Ruby Ray of Reversal&lt;/a&gt; will be attempted. Depending on the game difficulty selection, the Warden can use his &lt;a href=\"High-level%20class%20ability\"&gt;High-level class ability&lt;/a&gt; \"Improved Alacrity\", to cast several spells in succession in the same couple of rounds. The Warden has three prepared sequencers style spell casts ready to use:\nThe &lt;a href=\"Golem%20Construction%20for%20Spellcasters\"&gt;Golem Construction for Spellcasters&lt;/a&gt; mod places a special \"Ruby\" component in the Warden's inventory."}
{"id": "8849", "revid": "773742", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=8849", "title": "Prisoner of the Gnolls", "text": "This quest is obtained (and completed) by talking to &lt;a href=\"Ingot\"&gt;Ingot&lt;/a&gt; in the &lt;a href=\"Dryad%20Falls\"&gt;Dryad Falls&lt;/a&gt; area east of &lt;a href=\"Gnoll%20Stronghold\"&gt;Gnoll Stronghold&lt;/a&gt;. He wanted to roast and eat the prisoner &lt;a href=\"Dynaheir\"&gt;Dynaheir&lt;/a&gt;, going against the consensus of the Gnolls that keep her captive. For this, he was exiled from the &lt;a href=\"Gnoll%20Stronghold\"&gt;Gnoll Stronghold&lt;/a&gt;, and will tell the player about it as a revenge. If his description of Dynaheir's prison is anything to go by, it was intended at an earlier stage of game production to make another, underground, and literally a dungeon level at the &lt;a href=\"Gnoll%20Stronghold\"&gt;Gnoll Stronghold&lt;/a&gt;: \"...the otherrrs would rather let herrr live within that cellarrrr!..\" He brags that he will \"taste herrr flessh yet.\" If slain, he drops a unique halberd ( only): &lt;a href=\"The%20Chesley%20Crusher\"&gt;The Chesley Crusher&lt;/a&gt;, a +2 Halberd, with bonus damage.\nIt is not easy to both get his \"forrrtrrresss \"story (and the quest, for what it may be worth) and also kill him for his quite impressive loot, as he will not turn hostile and fight back once his tale is told. He will simply walk away, ignoring your attacks. You have to kill him before he can travel about 20 yards and disappear from the game. Any sort of stun effect (&lt;a href=\"Chromatic%20Orb\"&gt;Chromatic Orb&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Dart%20of%20Stunning\"&gt;Dart of Stunning&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"The%20Stupefier\"&gt;The Stupefier&lt;/a&gt;, etc.) will help greatly."}
{"id": "8894", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=8894", "title": "Priss", "text": "Priss is with &lt;a href=\"Rumar\"&gt;Rumar&lt;/a&gt; upstairs in the &lt;a href=\"Copper%20Coronet\"&gt;Copper Coronet&lt;/a&gt;.\nGameplay.\nPriss and Rumar are together engaging in the timeworn, passionate, and exciting practice of discreet infidelity.\nShould the party speak with her or Rumar, they will get the distinct impression that they don't want to be found out or disturbed by Rumar's wife &lt;a href=\"Tiana\"&gt;Tiana&lt;/a&gt;, who's downstairs looking for them.\nIf the party let's Tiana know the location of the two lovers, then if the party goes upstairs again to see what's going on, the two women will engage in a dagger fight to the death. Whomever is victorious will be praised by Rumar, and the couple will leave the Copper Coronet together. \nNotes.\nPriss's alignment in the original game is True Neutral, and it is changed to Chaotic Evil in the Enhanced Edition."}
{"id": "21758", "revid": "773742", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=21758", "title": "Pritchard's Family Stiletto", "text": "Pritchard's Family Stiletto is that may be encountered in \"\".\nAcquisition.\nDuring crossover actions between &lt;a href=\"Glint%20Gardnersonson%20%28quest%29\"&gt;Glint's companion quest&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"The%20Problem%20with%20Pritchard\"&gt;The Problem with Pritchard&lt;/a&gt;, if Pritchard is assaulted (for good reasons or otherwise), he may willingly give up this blade, or it may be taken from his dead body."}
