{"id": "38898", "revid": "47673695", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=38898", "title": "Purple Crystal", "text": "The Purple Crystal is north of\u00a0&lt;a href=\"The%20Magnificent%20Fil\"&gt;The Magnificent Fil&lt;/a&gt; in the &lt;a href=\"Resurrection%20Gorge\"&gt;Resurrection Gorge&lt;/a&gt;, behind about numerous &lt;a href=\"Ankheg\"&gt;Ankheg&lt;/a&gt;s. The Magnificent Fil asks &lt;a href=\"Gorion%27s%20Ward\"&gt;Gorion's Ward&lt;/a&gt; to retrieve the Purple Crystal and, in exchange, The Magnificent Fil will provide Gorion's Ward with &lt;a href=\"Fil%27s%20Summoning%20Stone\"&gt;Fil's Summoning Stone&lt;/a&gt;, which is needed for &lt;a href=\"Dorn%27s%20bloody%20path\"&gt;Dorn's bloody path&lt;/a&gt;"}
{"id": "30117", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=30117", "title": "Purple Globe", "text": "Colored globes are produced by interacting with the &lt;a href=\"Globe%20Machine\"&gt;Globe Machine&lt;/a&gt;, located on the &lt;a href=\"Watcher%27s%20Keep%20Final%20Seal\"&gt;Watcher's Keep Final Seal&lt;/a&gt; dungeon level.\nSelect which globe color is desired in the dialogue box presented by the machine. The machine can produce red, blue, green and purple globes, and a limit of four of each color. \nWhen the button is pressed to select a globe, the dialogue box displays a text, reading:\nPurple globes - gameplay.\nAll four purple globes look identical, except three of them will have a numeric \"1\" displayed on them, indicating a use \"charge\". This means that particular globe is a consumable/usable item.\nAs there isn't any information about what the globes do, the party would need to experiment and see the results. This feature is avoided by the wiki filling in that information.\nEven so, it may prove difficult to remember which globe does what, especially later in the adventure when managing an inventory. It will be up to the player to come up with some kind of tracking method.\nBugs.\nAs of BG2EE 2.6, The Purple Globe that heals the caster was asking for a target when none was required. This is identified and corrected in &lt;a href=\"The%20Enhanced%20Edition%20Fixpack%20%28EEFP%29\"&gt;The Enhanced Edition Fixpack (EEFP)&lt;/a&gt;. Ref: (globpur4.itm)"}
{"id": "39393", "revid": "47673695", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=39393", "title": "Purple Oil", "text": "The Purple Oil can be found in the &lt;a href=\"Watcher%27s%20Keep%20Illithid%20Encampment\"&gt;Illithid Encampment&lt;/a&gt;'s western-most room. The &lt;a href=\"Flint%20and%20Tinder\"&gt;Flint and Tinder&lt;/a&gt; can be used with this oil to light the torches nearby &lt;a href=\"Watcher%27s%20Keep%20Machine%20of%20Lum%20the%20Mad\"&gt;the Machine of Lum the Mad&lt;/a&gt;. When lit correctly, the torches will open the door to the adjacent room, which contains the &lt;a href=\"Crystal%20Mallet\"&gt;Crystal Mallet&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "9623", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=9623", "title": "Put the Spirit of the Child Wellyn to Rest", "text": "Put the Spirit of the Child Wellyn to Rest is a side quest in .\nAcquisition.\nThe first time you enter the &lt;a href=\"Athkatla%20Graveyard\"&gt;Athkatla Graveyard&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0in the evening or at night (hour 19+), a spirit of a &lt;a href=\"Wellyn\"&gt;small, halfling boy&lt;/a&gt; will glide toward the party. \nHe explains that he was murdered, but he cannot rest in peace until he has his teddy bear, &lt;a href=\"Littleman%20the%20Stuffed%20Bear\"&gt;Littleman&lt;/a&gt;, in his possession again. He says that a man named &lt;a href=\"Llynis\"&gt;Llynis&lt;/a&gt; was the murderer, and that he abducted Littleman. He asks that you get his teddy bear back for him so that he can finally rest. He also knows this murderer's current location.\nWalkthrough.\nThe murderer is Llynis, and has a room at the &lt;a href=\"Copper%20Coronet\"&gt;Copper Coronet&lt;/a&gt; in the &lt;a href=\"Athkatla%20Slums\"&gt;Athkatla Slums&lt;/a&gt;. The room is the westernmost of the suite of rooms on the upper floor. (In order to get access to the inn's back-rooms, you have to advance the quest &lt;a href=\"Investigate%20activities%20in%20the%20Copper%20Coronet%27s%20rooms\"&gt;Investigate activities in the Copper Coronet's rooms&lt;/a&gt; first.)\nThe party can can either try to pickpocket it from him or confront him about it. Although Llynis is a thief by trade, he is apparently not very good at noticing being pick pocketed himself.\nIf you confront him and ask for the bear, depending on the dialogue option you choose, Llynis will either attack you, or hand the bear over peacefully. Either way, you might as well loot his room when he's gone.\nReturn to the graveyard in the evening or at night and speak to Wellyn again. He will be so happy and will finally be able to rest in peace. The party receives .\nLater on, visit Wellyn's grave site in the morning and speak to his parents (named \"Mourners\" in-game). They will be overjoyed that their little boy can finally sleep peacefully. The party will get an additional 5,000 XP.\nNotes.\nIf the player is not interested in returning the Littleman stuffed bear to Wellyn's spirit then a dialogue option can be selected, as follows:\nAnd in an angry hoarse whisper Wellyn will reply:\nAfter this the spirit transforms into a &lt;a href=\"Revenant%20%28Valley%20of%20the%20Tombs%29\"&gt;Revenant&lt;/a&gt; creature and attacks in rage at the party's selfish attitude. Defend yourself! \nIf this occurs, then obviously no experience point awards are made available from the spirit or his parents. \nAchievements.\nBest Friends.\nReturn &lt;a href=\"Wellyn\"&gt;Wellyn&lt;/a&gt;'s &lt;a href=\"Littleman%20the%20Stuffed%20Bear\"&gt;missing bear&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "8347", "revid": "3234315", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=8347", "title": "Pyrgam Aleson", "text": "Pyrgam Aleson was a citizen of &lt;a href=\"Saradush\"&gt;Saradush&lt;/a&gt; and the owner of the &lt;a href=\"Tankard%20Tree\"&gt;Tankard Tree&lt;/a&gt; inn. Like many other residents of the city, Pyrgram Aleson did not like all the &lt;a href=\"Bhaalspawn\"&gt;Bhaalspawn&lt;/a&gt; in the area, as he believed they were the ones that attracted chaos to the city, most notably &lt;a href=\"Yaga-Shura\"&gt;Yaga-Shura's&lt;/a&gt; siege. He also despised the ruler of Saradush, &lt;a href=\"Gromnir%20Il-Khan\"&gt;Gromnir Il-Khan&lt;/a&gt;, due to his cowardice and foolishness."}
{"id": "50659", "revid": "280026", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=50659", "title": "Qadeel", "text": "\"'Qadeel\" is a merchant trader found by the waterside docking area in the &lt;a href=\"Bridge%20District\"&gt;Bridge District&lt;/a&gt;, he is supervising the loading of merchandise onto a nearby ship. The encounter has voice acting on some lines.\nWhen you first see him (he has the \"fat Man\" animation) he'll be with two Dockhand &lt;a href=\"Ogre\"&gt;Ogre&lt;/a&gt;s. When you get within a certain range with a party member, Qadeel can be overheard with a raised voice saying \"Work faster, you useless dogs! Faster, I say! We shall never have the ships loaded on time if you continue to be so lazy!\"\nThe Dockhand Ogres complain and tell him that one of them is sick - it grunts \"Gurgh be sick! Sick! He must slow, master!\". Qadeel starts shouting again saying \"Don't force me to get the whip out, you moronic twits! Keep loading, I say! KEEP LOADING!\"\nAt this point some of your party members may have some interjections about this, such as Valygar or Aerie. Afterwards the ogres lose control and begin threatening Qadeel in a fit of rage.\nYou can now do nothing and watch what happens or try and save Qadeel's skin by attacking the Ogres, or you could help the poor brutes out and put Qadeel in an early grave, or just let the Ogres handle the killing by themselves. If you intercede on his behalf, Qadeel will have some thankful dialogue. He'll hand you a reward of 200 gold, and the party gains 6.500 XP. If you get rid of Qadeel by way of violence, the Ogres will just lumber off and leave - now free of being abused. The Ogres are only worth 270 XP each. If your party wishes, they can loot Qadeel's smushed, crushed and slushed body for 200 gold, which should clean-up nicely with a little elbow grease.\nFor an extra 3500 XP you can kill Quadeel *after* talking to him to get the above reward with no implications on your reputation.\nMore parting comments are possible, from Jaheria. Thus ends the dockside ruckus. The local Ogre Stevedore Union is apparently quite weak in Athkatla."}
{"id": "49806", "revid": "773742", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=49806", "title": "Qais Ra'id", "text": "Qais Ra'id is one of three human Magicians (as they refer to themselves as Sha'ir or Zaharan magicians according to Hexxat) within the library chamber of the &lt;a href=\"Tomb%20of%20the%20Unproved\"&gt;Tomb of the Unproved&lt;/a&gt;. These magicians have an extended lifespan. Qais is part of Hexxat's second quest, to obtain the &lt;a href=\"Shroud%20of%20the%20Unproved\"&gt;Shroud of the Unproved&lt;/a&gt; for her master \"L\" (Larloch). \nGame Play.\nEach magician has some dialogue, which will begin when Hexxat enters the library, and if she is visible. Diya al-Hafiz initiates the dialogue. All dialogue choices eventually lead to hostility with the magicians.\nOnce Hostile, the magicians cast Spell Deflection and Stoneskin, followed by an obscure reference to a \"Tatoo of Power' or other \"Tatoo\" variations - this is just embellished text for dramatic effect (there is no \"Tatoo of Power\" spell in the game). Mirror images may be cast, perhaps Power Word, Silence. Offensively they will use Greater Malison and Lightning Bolts or Chain Lightning. Most of their memorized spells are not used. They do not attempt to Breach a target, nor do they try and take down any spell protections. They will cast a single target spell at a party member that is protected from single target spells, like Spell Deflection or Spell Trap. \nOne peculiar thing about these spell casters is that thy all cast the same spell, at the same target, at the same time. For instance, you might be on the receiving end of three Greater Malison, or three Power Word, Silence spells.\nThe AI for these creatures is not very adaptable, and does not react to what spells or protections your party has up. They do not move out of clouds or AOE spells if there are no opponents in their visual range. If anyone is within their visual range they will attempt to close the distance to cast spells at them. They cannot open the door to the library if you close it, but they will follow the party if the door is left open. For example, you could fire a &lt;a href=\"Cloudkill\"&gt;Cloudkill&lt;/a&gt; into the library, then close the door, and you may slay the whole group without any dialogue being uttered. These creatures are humans, not Undead or ghosts of some sort. They have no special immunities, or secret buffs. Their undroppable Stoneskin amulet does however provide them with at least one instance of Stoneskin.\nAlthough Qais is a level 20 Sorcerer, he has no memorized 8th or 9th level spells. Qais also is provided with four memorized Cleric Spells.\nMod Content.\nInstallation of &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Revisions\"&gt;Spell Revisions&lt;/a&gt; Mod will update this creature's spell book to the SR versions. For instance, instead of the 5th level spell &lt;a href=\"Chaos\"&gt;Chaos&lt;/a&gt; cast at the party, it will be the SR spell \"Waves of Fatigue\". Instead of the 7th Level Spell &lt;a href=\"Mantle\"&gt;Mantle&lt;/a&gt;, it will the SR version \"Prismatic Mantle\"."}
{"id": "48392", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=48392", "title": "Qar Jysstev", "text": "Qar Jyssteve is a nobleman member of the &lt;a href=\"Council%20of%20Six\"&gt;Council of Six&lt;/a&gt; who resides in &lt;a href=\"Athkatla\"&gt;Athkatla's&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Athkatla%20Government\"&gt;Government District&lt;/a&gt; during the \"\" campaign. He can be found in his home, the &lt;a href=\"Jysstev%20Estate\"&gt;Jyssteve Estate&lt;/a&gt; along with his wife, &lt;a href=\"Lady%20Jysstev\"&gt;Lady Jysteve&lt;/a&gt;.\nAs most nobles go, he is as snobbish as any others, but at least he will talk to you directly instead of those who talk amongst themselves as if you were not even there. For instance, not that he cares, he will ask, \"From which of the temples are you?\"\n\"It makes no nevermind to me, and I think it matters little to Sir Sarles as well. He's concerned with the creation, not with who might own his work.\"\nQar seems to care more about his own Status Coup than anything else saying.\"It's a great honor to have him here. We are simply the height of the social circuit right now. The envy of all the nobles, we are.\"And with that he brushes you off.\"Do try and keep to the sides while here, will you? I've very wealthy people coming to see the artist, and I don't want people dawdling with the messengers.\""}
